sentences: Jerry Neil Capehart (August 22, 1928 – June 7, 1998) was an American songwriter and music manager.
Capehart co-wrote the songs "Summertime Blues" and "C'mon Everybody" with Eddie Cochran, whom he also managed.
Eddie Cochran's 1958 recordings of Capehart compositions reached No. 8 and No. 35 respectively on the Billboard Pop chart.
Other notable songs written by Capehart are "Beautiful Brown Eyes" recorded by Rosemary Clooney which reached No. 11 on Billboard Pop chart in 1951 and "Turn Around, Look

At Me", which was Glen Campbell's first hit single, peaking at No. 15 on Billboard Adult Contemporary chart in 1961, and sparked The Vogues' seven remakes on the Hot 100 during 1968-1969, peaking at No. 7.

In 1994, country music artist Alan Jackson scored a No. 1 hit with his recording of "Summertime Blues".
